Fanya chini are similar to fanya juus except that the soil is put on the lower side of the contour trench. Typically identified by the author.

fertilizer-desc: The section is used to collect and record fertilizer data from literature sources that describe the type, amount, and timing of fertilizer applications for a particular crop or system.  There are two main components of this section:
fert-subdesc-1: Elemental NPK: Elemental NPK refers to the three primary macronutrients that are essential for plant growth: nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K). These elements are typically found in fertilizers and soil amendments, and their concentrations are often listed as an amount of the total weight of the product.
fert-subdesc-2: Fertilizer components: This includes collecting information on what the fertilizer application contains, the total amount applied and the timing of application.
fert-subdesc-3: Note: Organic fertilizers include manure and compost, however, the application of plant mulches are collected in the ‘Mulch’ section.

microcatchments-b52-description: Microcatchment is a term for infield water catchment. Negarim microcatchments, for example, are diamond-shaped basins surrounded by small earth bunds with an infiltration pit in the lowest corner of each. Runoff is collected from within the basin and stored in the infiltration pit. Microcatchments are mainly used for growing trees or bushes. Typically identified by the author.

mulch-herb-mixed-n-fixing-non-n-fixing-b: Mulching with a mixture of herbaceous plant residues from both nitrogen-fixing (leguminous) and non-nitrogen fixing plant, residues remain on soil surface and are not incorporated or burnt (for example).

other-desc: In this section, we will focus on non-ERA practices that have the potential to impact the structure of data entry. To determine if a practice influences data entry, we consider whether the results would differ if the 'other practice' is not taken into account. If the answer is 'yes', then we conclude that the practice structures data entry.

ph-amendment-desc: The purpose of this section is to collect information of the pH amendment practices used in the literature. Soil pH amendment refers to the process of adjusting the pH level of soil by adding materials such as lime, sulfur, or other soil amendments to increase or decrease the acidity or alkalinity of the soil.

ridge-furrow-b71-2-description: The mounding of soil to allow movement and storage of water in a furrow next to the ridge. Ridges are usually remade each season. Record ridge and furrow as a conventional practice if it is the base practice else use the direction of comparison to classify if it is reduced (e.g. when compared to more tillage) or conventional (e.g. compared to no-till).
sites-desc:
Here we record the geographic co-ordinates of where an experiment has taken place and the uncertainty associated with this. You can record multiple locations.

For each site you can also capture general biophysical information about the site and the starting conditions that describe the soils of the site.

stone-rows-b45-description: Stones piled in rows within a field, typically along contour lines, for the purpose of rainwater harvesting or soil water conservation.
supplemental-b54-description: The use of irrigation to augment growth, but not applied continuously. Could also be called intermittent irrigation.
terraces-b70-description: The soil of steeply sloping fields is dug into large steps.
tied-ridges-b71-3-description: Basins are made by digging out shallow furrows along the contour lines of a slope and making ridges on the downside of the furrows. These are “tied” together by slightly lower ridges which are made at regular intervals along the furrows. If teid ridges are dug one year and then kept across many seasons, after season one this can be considered a form of reduced tillage, this will typically be identified by the author.
tillage-desc: Tillage the agriculture practice of preparing the soil for planting. If you have a base practice of conventional tillage you cannot have reduced or no-tillage as an experimental practice and vice-versa.
tillage-subdesc-1: Ridge & Furrow is "Conventional" if there is no comparison to practice with more intensive tillage (e.g. mouldboard plough), if it is compared to a more intensive tillage practice then it is recorded "Reduced".

water-harvesting-subdesc-1: Note: Since these practices can overlap with tillage methods, they can be recorded in both sections.
